title: No, Don't Do Palantir for AI - Brendan Falk, Hercules
description:
*From Enterprise AI to Developer Tools: The Hard Truths of Building Palantir for AI* Brendan Falk, founder and CEO of Zeus (now Hercules), joins us for a candid conversation about his pivot away from building enterprise AI transformations for Global 2000 companies. After leaving his role as Global AI Lead at Amazon's private equity business development team, where he worked with hundreds of PE-backed companies on AI initiatives, Brendan launched Zeus with a bold vision: become the Palantir for AI transformations. The model seemed perfect on paper - target Fortune 500 companies with $5-10 million contracts, build custom AI agents for any use case, and leverage a proprietary platform to maintain high margins. But six months in, the reality hit hard. From insurance RFPs with Excel spreadsheets embedded in Word documents to the crushing weight of ongoing maintenance costs, Brendan shares the unvarnished truth about why the economics didn't work.

title: Navigating Data Chaos A New Approach
How 3 Founders Generated $1M ARR in 9 Weeks Without a Single SDR
description:
In this episode, Lior is joined by Amos Bar-Joseph, co-founder and CEO of Swann, a two-time exited founder now building a radically different, AI-native company. Amos shares the playbook for the "Autonomous Business," a model aiming for an unprecedented $10 million in ARR per employee. He details how Swann is on a mission to hit $30 million in ARR with just its three founders and a sophisticated ecosystem of AI agents. 

Amos provides a masterclass in applied AI, breaking down how Swann built an entire go-to-market engine that generated over $1 million in ARR in just nine weeks without a single SDR. We explore their internal agents like "Shakespeare" for content, "The Observer" for lead intelligence, and "The Connector" for automated outreach. Amos explains the critical difference between simple AI automation and true AI agents, and how designing with human-in-the-loop and feedback mechanisms is key to unlocking the 100x version of your team. 

This is a look into the future of lean, h â€¦

title: ACQ2: How to Live in Everyone Else's Future (with Shopify CEO Tobi LÃ¼tke)
description:
Tobi is one of the most thoughtful people in the technology industry. He's also one of the very few people who started as a programmer -- just trying to solve his own problem -- and still runs his company as CEO today even as it approaches a $200B market cap. Tobi has done this in two big ways: first, a willingness throw away his past beliefs in the face of new data, growing into the leader the company needed. And second, by remaining a close observer (and participant!) in how new technology emerges that changes what is possible.

Today on ACQ2, we talk with him about both. The first half of the episode is about what has changed for him in the AI era. How he spends his time with AI throughout the day, how he thinks about what AI unlocks philosophically, and what he thinks the impact will be on all of us and what we build. The second half is more about Shopify. How he dealt mentally with the explosion in stock price in 2021 from a 20x revenue multiple to a 70x revenue multiple. And then â€¦

title: Balaji Srinivasan | Modern Politics and Starting a New Country
description:
(If you enjoyed this, please like and subscribe!)

Balaji Srinivasan is an angel investor, tech founder, and WSJ bestselling author of The Network State. He is currently the founder of The Network School, a frontier community for techno-optimists.

Formerly the CTO of Coinbase and General Partner at Andreessen Horowitz, he is an early investor in many successful tech companies, including Anduril, Perplexity, OpenSea, Alchemy, StarkWare, Dapper Labs, Benchling, and Polymarket to name a few. Balaji also led the launch of USDC as Coinbase CTO, and was an early investor in many important crypto protocols including Bitcoin, Ethereum, and Solana among others.

In this conversation, we discuss the evolving political landscape, emphasizing the disruptions caused by technology and the internet. Balaji outlines the four factions in the current political climate: the internet, Blue America, Red America, and China. We also explore the implications of tariffs, the rise of AI, and the future of netw â€¦
